<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="386" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="6.[175,1381,2336,2997]" pageId="6" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,414,2647,2680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="386">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
The Gambian Slit-faced Bat roosts during the day in hollow trees, caves, and abandoned buildings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="386" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[175,1381,2336,2997]" pageId="6" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[176,884,2726,2759]" pageId="6" pageNumber="386">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
The Gambian Slit-faced Bat roosts in small or large groups of up to ¢.50 individuals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="386" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="6.[175,1381,2336,2997]" pageId="6" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[177,533,2805,2838]" pageId="6" pageNumber="386">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List. Due to its wide distribution and flexible habitat requirements, the Gambian Slitfaced Bat is unlikely to become threatened in the near future.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
